So for the past 26 years, part of my story has included chronic illness and disability, a body that more often than not is hard to live in and even harder to call good, let alone God's definition, which is very good.

00:49:01.890 --> 00:49:09.300
Pain, numbness, dissociative seizures, nausea, the laundry list of undiagnosable issues kind of goes on and on.

00:49:11.083 --> 00:49:14.107
And those symptoms have led to anger.

00:49:14.147 --> 00:49:19.094
They've led to great questions and severe suffering in my life.

00:49:20.536 --> 00:49:30.610
But I'd say in this body, not in spite of it, but because of the limits it has, I have also experienced the incredible nearness of a perfect God.

00:49:31.170 --> 00:49:37.558
who in suffering not only joins me but he goes before me and he's behind me and he walks beside me in that suffering.

00:49:40.001 --> 00:49:42.084
So God, this is who he is.

00:49:42.144 --> 00:49:50.214
He takes the small and the large deaths that we all experience and he breathes resurrection life into what seems unredeemable.

00:49:50.454 --> 00:49:51.816
This is the business that he's in.

00:49:51.856 --> 00:49:57.042
So when you walk through suffering, God grieves alongside you

00:49:57.762 --> 00:50:07.394
And the Spirit animates the Scripture that we read day in and day out, the promises of when we fix our eyes not on what's seen but what's eternal, we gain this perspective that can't be replaced.

00:50:08.815 --> 00:50:18.848
We lift our eyes to a God who holds the universe in his hands but he willingly lowered himself to the confines of a body that experienced the greatest suffering.

00:50:20.189 --> 00:50:27.378
We're temples of the Holy Spirit because God is powerful enough to let us take on the identity of Christ.

00:50:29.186 --> 00:50:39.277
So the invitation before us now in communion is to remember the good news of Jesus, which says, this is my body broken for you.

00:50:40.839 --> 00:50:48.727
So as we come to the table, we follow Jesus' command to remember, not just his miracles or his profound words, but most importantly, his broken body.

00:50:49.948 --> 00:50:54.673
What looks like death to us is where God comes near and gives life to the full.

00:50:56.776 --> 00:50:58.898
So before we take communion,

00:50:59.170 --> 00:51:12.147
Can we just take 15 to 20 seconds right now, say, come Holy Spirit, and just say submit to Him that small or big death that you're carrying right now in this moment, and invite Him into it.

00:51:12.368 --> 00:51:13.609
No solutions for Him?

00:51:14.390 --> 00:51:15.472
Just let Him do His work.

00:51:15.492 --> 00:51:17.735
Holy Spirit, would you come, would you enter?

00:51:17.755 --> 00:51:23.282
The things that seem unredeemable in our lives at this very moment.

00:51:27.362 --> 00:51:31.247
Thanks for joining the Bridgetown family as we engage in this teaching series.

00:51:31.948 --> 00:51:37.896
To learn more about the life of our church and how you can get involved, visit Bridgetown.church slash welcome.

00:51:38.657 --> 00:51:46.768
If you're interested in contributing financially to Bridgetown Church and to our ministry, you can do that at Bridgetown.church slash giving.

00:51:47.529 --> 00:51:56.882
Wherever you're joining us from, we hope this resource blesses you and encourages you to be with Jesus, become like Jesus, and do what Jesus did.
